---
import CaseStudy from "../../layouts/CaseStudy.astro";

const metrics = [
    { value: "6 months", label: "As PM" },
    { value: "MVP", label: "Stage" },
    { value: "LLMs + n8n", label: "Tech stack" },
];
---

<CaseStudy
    title="Building an AI-powered patent intelligence platform"
    tag="AI Product · Intellectual Property"
    metrics={metrics}
>
    <section>
        <h2>Context</h2>
        <p>
            Patentia is an AI-native platform that helps researchers,
            innovators, and technology transfer offices evaluate patentability
            before investing in formal patent applications. The platform
            combines semantic search across 165M+ patents with AI-generated
            patentability assessments and patent drafts.
        </p>
        <p>
            I joined the team as Product Manager when the product was at MVP
            stage — a working but early version with no customers yet, and a
            roadmap still taking shape.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Challenge</h2>
        <p>
            Early-stage AI products in the IP space face a specific trust
            problem: potential users — researchers and innovators — are
            reluctant to share confidential invention details with an AI system
            before understanding how their data is handled.
        </p>
        <p>
            Beyond trust, the product needed structure. Discovery,
            prioritization, and delivery processes had to be built from the
            ground up while the team was simultaneously building the product.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>My role</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>
                Led product discovery and user research with universities,
                researchers, and innovation teams
            </li>
            <li>Defined and maintained the product roadmap and backlog</li>
            <li>Facilitated Agile ceremonies and kept delivery on track</li>
            <li>Defined user personas and mapped adoption barriers</li>
            <li>Translated research insights into product requirements</li>
            <li>Created wireframes for key product flows</li>
            <li>Structured Jira for backlog and sprint management</li>
            <li>
                Worked with LLM-based workflows and prompt engineering in the
                context of product validation
            </li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Product decisions</h2>
        <p>
            One of the most important early decisions was identifying that the
            core adoption barrier was not the technology — it was trust. Users
            needed to understand how their IP data was protected before engaging
            with the platform.
        </p>
        <p>
            This shaped how the product communicated its value: security and
            confidentiality became part of the product experience, not just the
            marketing.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Key learning</h2>
        <p>
            Building AI products at MVP stage requires balancing speed with
            trust. Features matter less than the user's confidence that the
            product is safe to use. Identifying that barrier early — through
            research rather than assumptions — was the most valuable
            contribution I could make as PM.
        </p>
    </section>
</CaseStudy>
